{"title_page": "Nancy Spender", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2018}}\n{{Use British English|date=February 2018}}\n'''Nancy Spender''' (29 October 1909 &ndash; 20 June 2001) was a British painter, described on her death as \"much underrated\".<ref name=\"Telegraph obit\" />\n\nNancy Culliford Sharp<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/10.1093/ref:odnb/9780198614128.001.0001/odnb-9780198614128-e-75976 | doi=10.1093/ref:odnb/75976| title=The Oxford Dictionary of National Biography| year=2004}}</ref> was born on 29 October 1909 in [[Truro]], [[Cornwall]], daughter of Dr Hugh Culliford Sharp, [[C.B.E.]], medical officer for the city of Truro.<ref>Debrett's Peerage, Baronetage and Knightage, ed. C. F. J. Hankinson, 1955, p. 3147</ref><ref>The Municipal Journal and Public Works Engineer, vol. 37, collected issues 1823-1848, 1928, p. 475</ref> Her grandfather, Edward Sharp, had been a surgeon at Truro.<ref>Biographical History of Gonville and Caius College 1349-1897, ed. John Venn, vol II, 1713-1897, Cambridge University Press, 1898, p. 485</ref> She attended [[Cheltenham Ladies' College]] and the [[Slade School of Art]].<ref name=\"Guardian obit\" /> At the Slade she met and married her first husband, [[William Coldstream]], with whom she had two daughters.<ref name=\"Guardian obit\" />\n\nIn the late 1930s she had an affair with [[Louis MacNeice]], illustrating two of his books and partially inspiring ''[[Autumn Journal]]''.<ref name=\"Telegraph obit\" /> She met [[Michael Spender]] (brother of the poet [[Stephen Spender]]) at this time, and fell in love. In 1942 she divorced Coldstream and married Spender. She worked as an ambulance driver during the [[Second World War]]<ref name=\"Telegraph obit\" /> and her son [[Philip Spender]] was born in 1943.<ref name=\"Guardian obit\" /> Her second husband was killed in an air crash during the last week of the war. She took up work as an art teacher, which she continued till 1977.<ref name=\"Telegraph obit\" />\n\nNancy Spender's portrait paintings, [[still life]]s and landscapes were painted in a figurative, realist manner.<ref name=\"Guardian obit\" /> She exhibited regularly with the [[London Group]] and at the [[Royal Academy of Arts]].<ref name=\"Telegraph obit\" /> After her retirement she increased her output of paintings and etchings.<ref name=\"Telegraph obit\" /> Having little interest in commercial sales, she did not have her first solo exhibition until 1979, which was held in a [[West End of London|West End]] gallery run by a friend.<ref name=\"Guardian obit\" />\n\nNancy Spender died on 20 June 2001 aged 91.<ref name=\"Guardian obit\" />\n\nTwo of her portraits are now in the collection of the London's [[National Portrait Gallery, London|National Portrait Gallery]] and another is held at [[Sir John Soane's Museum]].<ref name=\"Guardian obit\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|refs=\n<ref name=\"Guardian obit\">{{cite news|author=John Margetson |title=Nancy Spender (obituary) |url=https://www.theguardian.com/news/2001/jun/25/guardianobituaries.arts |date=25 June 2001 |work=The Guardian |accessdate=6 January 2014}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Telegraph obit\">{{cite news|author= |title=Nancy Spender (obituary) |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/1310454/Nancy-Spender.html |date=27 June 2001 |work=The Telegraph |accessdate=6 January 2014}}</ref>\n}}\n\n==External Links==\n* [https://www.npg.org.uk/collections/search/person/mp09539 Portraits by Nancy Spender] in the collection of the [[National Portrait Gallery, London]]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Spender, Nancy}}\n[[Category:1909 births]]\n[[Category:2001 deaths]]\n[[Category:English women painters]]\n[[Category:People from Truro]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the Slade School of Fine Art]]\n[[Category:People educated at Cheltenham Ladies' College]]\n[[Category:20th-century English painters]]\n[[Category:20th-century British women artists]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2018}}\n{{Use British English|date=February 2018}}\n'''Nancy Spender''' (29 October 1909 &ndash; 20 June 2001) was a British painter, described on her death as \"much underrated\".<ref name=\"Telegraph obit\" />\n\nNancy Culliford Sharp<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/10.1093/ref:odnb/9780198614128.001.0001/odnb-9780198614128-e-75976 | doi=10.1093/ref:odnb/75976| title=The Oxford Dictionary of National Biography| year=2004}}</ref> was born on 29 October 1909 in [[Truro]], [[Cornwall]], daughter of Dr Hugh Culliford Sharp, [[C.B.E.]], medical officer for the city of Truro.<ref>Debrett's Peerage, Baronetage and Knightage, ed. C. F. J. Hankinson, 1955, p. 3147</ref><ref>The Municipal Journal and Public Works Engineer, vol. 37, collected issues 1823-1848, 1928, p. 475</ref> Her grandfather, Edward Sharp, had been a surgeon at Truro.<ref>Biographical History of Gonville and Caius College 1349-1897, ed. John Venn, vol II, 1713-1897, Cambridge University Press, 1898, p. 485</ref> She attended [[Cheltenham Ladies' College]] and the [[Slade School of Art]].<ref name=\"Guardian obit\" /> At the Slade she met and married her first husband, [[William Coldstream]], with whom she had two daughters.<ref name=\"Guardian obit\" />\n\nIn the late 1930s she had an affair with [[Louis MacNeice]], illustrating two of his books and partially inspiring ''[[Autumn Journal]]''.<ref name=\"Telegraph obit\" /> She met [[Michael Spender]] (brother of the poet [[Stephen Spender]]) at this time, and fell in love. In 1942 she divorced Coldstream and married Spender. She worked as an ambulance driver during the [[Second World War]]<ref name=\"Telegraph obit\" /> and her son [[Philip Spender]] was born in 1943.<ref name=\"Guardian obit\" /> Her second husband was killed in an air crash during the last week of the war. She took up work as an art teacher, which she continued till 1977.<ref name=\"Telegraph obit\" />\n\nNancy Spender's portrait paintings, [[still life]]s and landscapes were painted in a figurative, realist manner.<ref name=\"Guardian obit\" /> She exhibited regularly with the [[London Group]] and at the [[Royal Academy of Arts]].<ref name=\"Telegraph obit\" /> After her retirement she increased her output of paintings and etchings.<ref name=\"Telegraph obit\" /> Having little interest in commercial sales, she did not have her first solo exhibition until 1979, which was held in a [[West End of London|West End]] gallery run by a friend.<ref name=\"Guardian obit\" />\n\nNancy Spender died on 20 June 2001 aged 91.<ref name=\"Guardian obit\" />\n\nTwo of her portraits are now in the collection of the London's [[National Portrait Gallery, London|National Portrait Gallery]] and another is held at [[Sir John Soane's Museum]].<ref name=\"Guardian obit\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|refs=\n<ref name=\"Guardian obit\">{{cite news|author=John Margetson |title=Nancy Spender (obituary) |url=https://www.theguardian.com/news/2001/jun/25/guardianobituaries.arts |date=25 June 2001 |work=The Guardian |accessdate=6 January 2014}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Telegraph obit\">{{cite news|author= |title=Nancy Spender (obituary) |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/1310454/Nancy-Spender.html |date=27 June 2001 |work=The Telegraph |accessdate=6 January 2014}}</ref>\n}}\n\n==External Links==\n* [https://www.npg.org.uk/collections/search/person/mp09539 Portraits by Nancy Spender] in the collection of the [https://www.npg.org.uk/ National Portrait Gallery, London]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Spender, Nancy}}\n[[Category:1909 births]]\n[[Category:2001 deaths]]\n[[Category:English women painters]]\n[[Category:People from Truro]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the Slade School of Fine Art]]\n[[Category:People educated at Cheltenham Ladies' College]]\n[[Category:20th-century English painters]]\n[[Category:20th-century British women artists]]\n", "name_user": "Graham87", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal Links:use wikilink", "url_page"